Import SALMON read counts

## List all directories containing data 
samples <- list.files(full.names = F, pattern="20_.*x|30_.*x|c_.*x")

## Obtain a vector of all file names including the path
files <- file.path(samples, "quant.sf")
## Since all quant files have the same name it is useful to have names for each element
names(files) <- str_replace(samples, "~", "") %>% str_replace(".salmon", "")

txi <- tximport(files, type="salmon", tx2gene=data[,c("NODE", "IPR")] , countsFromAbundance="no")

## Create a sampletable
sampletype <- factor(c(rep("20_days",6),rep("30_days",6), rep("no_treatment", 6)))
meta <- data.frame(sampletype, row.names = colnames(txi$counts))

### Check that sample names match in both files
all(colnames(txi$counts) %in% rownames(meta))
## [1] TRUE

Distribution of variance for the raw read counts:

data_v <- txi$counts %>% 
  round() %>% 
  data.frame()

mean_counts <- apply(data_v[,1:18], 1, mean)
variance_counts <- apply(data_v[,1:18], 1, var)
df <- data.frame(mean_counts, variance_counts)

ggplot(df) +
  geom_point(aes(x=mean_counts, y=variance_counts)) + 
  scale_y_log10(limits = c(1,1e9)) +
  scale_x_log10(limits = c(1,1e9)) +

No signs of heteroscedasticity. For the genes with high mean expression, the variance across replicates tends to be greater than the mean - characteristic for RNaseq data. Data points do not fall on the diagonal - characteristic for RNAseq data.

Per-gene dispersion estimates and fitted mean-dispersion relationship

plotDispEsts(dds)

Red curve represents the maximum likelihood estimation (MLE) for the expected dispersion for genes of a given expression strength. Black dot is a gene with an associated mean expression level (mean of normalized counts) and MLE estimation of the dispersion (dispersion) Blue dots - gene values which were shrunk toward the curve for better dispersion estimation. Genes with blue circles have extremely high dispersion and were not shrunk to avoid false positives.

=> Data are mostly accumulated around the curve, that means that data fit well to the used model in DESeq2 (ok)

=> The dispersion is decreasing with increasing mean expression levels (ok)

=> A lot of shrunken genes because of the low number of samples.

Comparison 20 days vs control

contrast_20_c <- c("sampletype","20_days", "no_treatment")
res_table_20_c <- results(dds, contrast=contrast_20_c , alpha = 0.05)
res_table_20_c_shrunken <- lfcShrink(dds, contrast=contrast_20_c, res=res_table_20_c, type = "ashr")
## using 'ashr' for LFC shrinkage. If used in published research, please cite:
##     Stephens, M. (2016) False discovery rates: a new deal. Biostatistics, 18:2.
##     https://doi.org/10.1093/biostatistics/kxw041
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plotMA(res_table_20_c, alpha=0.05)
plotMA(res_table_20_c_shrunken, alpha=0.05, ylim=c(-5,6))

res_tableOE_20 <- res_table_20_c_shrunken %>%
  data.frame() %>% rownames_to_column(var="gene") %>% as_tibble()
res_tableOE_20<-as.data.frame(res_tableOE_20)

res_tableOE_20$diffexpressed <- "NO"
res_tableOE_20$diffexpressed[res_tableOE_20$log2FoldChange > 1.2 & res_tableOE_20$pvalue < 0.05] <- "UP"
res_tableOE_20$diffexpressed[res_tableOE_20$log2FoldChange < -1.2 & res_tableOE_20$pvalue < 0.05] <- "DOWN"

### VULCANO PLOT ###
# Create a new "label" column and set it to "NA" for all rows
res_tableOE_20$delabel <- rep(NA, nrow(res_tableOE_20))
res_tableOE_20 <- res_tableOE_20[order(-abs(res_tableOE_20$log2FoldChange)), ]

# Set the "gene" values for the DEG:
res_tableOE_20$delabel[res_tableOE_20$diffexpressed %in% c("UP", "DOWN")] <- res_tableOE_20$gene[res_tableOE_20$diffexpressed %in% c("UP", "DOWN")]

ggplot(data = res_tableOE_20, aes(x = log2FoldChange, y = -log10(pvalue), col = diffexpressed, label = delabel)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = c(-1.2, 1.2), col = "gray", linetype = 'dashed') +
  geom_hline(yintercept = -log10(0.05), col = "gray", linetype = 'dashed') +
  geom_point(size = 1.75) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c('#00a7c4', "grey", "#eb3c3f"), labels = c("Downregulated", "Not significant", "Upregulated")) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 21), xlim = c(-8, 8)) + 
  labs(color = 'Severe', x = expression("log"[2]*"FC"), y = expression("-log"[10]*"p-value")) +
  ggtitle('20 days vs control') +
  geom_text_repel(max.overlaps = 12, size = 3, color = "black")
